      <!-- ===== SECURITY & AI — applied practice ===== -->
      <section class="block" id="edge">
        <div class="num-tag reveal"><b>06</b> how I build</div>
        <h2 class="block-title reveal">Security practice and AI tooling, applied — not aspirational</h2>
        <p class="block-lede reveal">These aren't separate tracks from the engineering work above — they're how the work
          above gets built. Here's the direct line from each.</p>

        <div class="edge-grid">
          <div class="edge-col reveal">
            <h3>Cybersecurity, built into the backend</h3>
            <p class="edge-sub">Grounded in Google's Foundations of Cybersecurity and applied directly to production
              fintech systems — not shelved as a credential.</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Access control by design</strong> — API endpoints grouped by user role so a payment gateway
                client can't reach a mobile-only route, enforced at the framework level, not left to convention.</li>
              <li><strong>Secure authentication</strong> — JWT for mobile sessions and a generic OTP engine reused for
                both login and payment approval, so every new verification requirement inherits already-audited logic.
              </li>
              <li><strong>Payment-flow integrity</strong> — transaction verification and logging built so a failed or
                intercepted request can't silently corrupt financial records.</li>
              <li><strong>Multi-tenant isolation</strong> — access rules that guarantee one company's data and admins
                can never leak into another's on a shared backend.</li>
              <li><strong>Audit-first refactoring</strong> — reviewing inherited code for security-relevant issues
                before writing a line of the fix.</li>
              <li><strong>Anti-fraud-ready architecture</strong> — API grouping built so a fraud-detection layer can be
                added platform-wide later without touching individual endpoints.</li>
              <li><strong>Hands-on offensive security practice</strong> — sharpening real-world attack/defense thinking
                through labs on TryHackMe, Hack The Box, and PortSwigger's Web Security Academy, using Burp Suite for
                manual request inspection and testing.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="edge-col reveal">
            <h3>AI as a daily engineering tool</h3>
            <p class="edge-sub">Used to move faster through architecture, review, and documentation — without lowering
              the bar on security or clean code.</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Claude &amp; Claude Code</strong> — architecture and refactor planning, and scaffolding new
                Odoo modules faster while keeping the API framework consistent across the codebase.</li>
              <li><strong>ChatGPT &amp; Codex</strong> — rapid prototyping, boilerplate generation, and a second pass on
                edge cases before code reaches human review.</li>
              <li><strong>AI-assisted documentation</strong> — keeping OpenAPI/Swagger specs and internal docs in sync
                with the code as it actually changes.</li>
              <li><strong>Faster audits</strong> — I do the actual audit and judgment calls myself; AI tooling just
                helps me track findings across a large inherited codebase and keep them organized as I work through the
                manual review.</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="edge-note">Net effect: <strong>shorter iteration cycles</strong>, with security review and
              Odoo's own design patterns still the final word on what ships.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

